### Footnotes

<span id="fn_299"></span>[121:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_300.md) Corresponding to
the eighteenth word, yim, in the Ahunavair, according to E. P. Riv.; but
it is the nineteenth Nask in other Rivâyats. This name, which is here
written like Zakî-hat-min, should probably be Zîk-a*î*t-tûm, meaning
'the most intimate concerns,' as the Nask refers chiefly to personal and
family law; but it is called Askâram, or Sakadâm, in the Rivâyats, which
also state that it contained fifty-two kardah, fargar*d*s, or vê*d*ast;
thus agreeing with the total of the sections mentioned in Chaps.
XXXVIII, XLI.

<span id="fn_300"></span>[121:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_302.md) It is possible to
read yêdatô, 'sacred being,' instead of dâ*d*ŏ, 'law.'

<span id="fn_301"></span>[122:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_303.md) To protect it from
the demons who are supposed to be specially dangerous during the first
three nights.

<span id="fn_302"></span>[122:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_304.md) Equivalent to
'mid-spring butter,' the Av. maidhyô-zaremaya, 'mid-verdure,' being the
season corresponding to the middle of the second Parsi month, which was
early in May when the year commenced at the vernal equinox (see Bd. XXV,
6, 21).

<span id="fn_303"></span>[123:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_305.md) See Chap. XVII, 6.

<span id="fn_304"></span>[123:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_306.md) This passage
appears to refer to that quoted in Farh. Oîm, p. 38, ll. 8, 9; though
the latter part of Chap. XLI, 19 is more applicable to ll. 4-8 of the
same page.

<span id="fn_305"></span>[124:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_307.md) Or *g*âmak may
mean 'a cup.'

<span id="fn_306"></span>[124:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_308.md) Reading min
gûnagîhâ.

<span id="fn_307"></span>[125:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_309.md) See Dd. XXXIX, 1
n.

<span id="fn_308"></span>[126:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_310.md) Intended for
ceremonial purification.

<span id="fn_309"></span>[127:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_311.md) For irrigation.

<span id="fn_310"></span>[127:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_312.md) Reading virûnag,
but the word is miswritten nîrang-î.

<span id="fn_311"></span>[128:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_313.md) In the shape of
sluices for regulating the supply of water for irrigation.

<span id="fn_312"></span>[129:1](sbe37041.htm#fr_314.md) Instead of khar
va-khazûrâ, the MS. has khôr va-zak-î ras.

<span id="fn_313"></span>[129:2](sbe37041.htm#fr_315.md) Assuming that
